Question 1

Short Description

there are 15 variables and 1384617 observations in this dataset. It contains details including user id: customer identifier, order id: order identifier, product id: product identifier, product name, reordered if it is reordered or not. Also, in the local store, there are 21 departments.

Answers to question

1.There are 134 aisles in the store. And among them, fresh vegetables ordered the most.

instacart %>% 
  group_by(aisle) %>%
  summarize(n_obs = n())%>%
  filter(n_obs>10000)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = aisle,y=n_obs)) +
  geom_bar(stat='identity') +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(x = "aisles", 
       y = "log10 of total number of items", 
       title = "Item ordered by aisle") +
  coord_flip()

3.

instacart %>% 
  filter(aisle %in% c("baking ingredients", "dog food care", "packaged vegetables fruits")) %>% 
  group_by(aisle, product_name) %>% 
  summarise(item_sum = n()) %>% 
  group_by(aisle) %>% 
  mutate(item_rank = min_rank(desc(item_sum))) %>% 
  filter(item_rank == 1) %>% 
  knitr::kable(digits = 1)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'aisle'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

instacart %>% 
  filter(product_name %in% c("Pink Lady Apples", "Coffee Ice Cream")) %>% 
  select(product_name, order_dow, order_hour_of_day) %>% 
  group_by(product_name, order_dow) %>% 
  summarise(mean_hour = mean(order_hour_of_day)) %>% 
  spread(key = order_dow, value = mean_hour) %>% 
  rename(Sunday = "0", Monday = "1", Tuesday = "2", Wednesday = "3", Thursday = "4", Friday = "5", Saturday = "6") %>% 
  knitr::kable(digit = 1)

there are 6 variables and 50400 observations in this dataset. It contains details including week: week identifier, day id: date identifier, daytype: identify if it is weekday(Monday to Friday) or weekend (Saturday to Sunday). The original activity is pivot into activity_countsand activity_day .

accel%>%

The activity in Wednesday and Friday is significantly higher than the activity counts in Saturday.

accel%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=activitiy_day,y=activity_counts,color=day))+
  geom_point(alpha=.2)+
  geom_smooth(aes(group=day))+
  labs(
    title="24 hour activity accrose each day",
    x="Hour",
    y="Activity")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

In this conclude that the activity on Friday morning is the highest while the activity on Sunday afternoon is the second highest. The activity around noon is the lowest accrose the day.
